\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
In either case, we have reduced the system to the two equations 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{1}-v_{2}=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $3v_{2}-2v_{3}=0$
\end_inset

, from which the solution follows.
 Just as synthetic division would be useful even if its only purpose were
 to help people quickly divide polynomials by degree one binomials, this
 matrix approach to solving systems would be useful even if its only purpose
 were to help organize people's thoughts as they solved linear systems.
 As will be shown in the coming chapters, the ideas laid out here will have
 profound consequences.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What should be taken from the matrix solution of the system
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{array}{ccccccc}
-29v_{1} & + & 14v_{2} & + & 10v_{3} & = & 0\\
-76v_{1} & + & 37v_{2} & + & 26v_{3} & = & 0\\
6v_{1} & - & 3v_{2} & - & 2v_{3} & = & 0
\end{array}
\]

\end_inset

shown above is the fact that three row operations is enough to mirror the
 process of elimination using matrices.
 On the matrix side, we swapped rows, multiplied rows by a nonzero constant,
 and most of all added multiples of one row to another.
 Everything done in solving a linear system can be modeled by one of these
 operations on the corresponding matrix.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An amazing array of deep results in linear algebra stem from the careful
 understanding of row operations and their consequences.
 As such, these three operations are called 
\series bold
elementary row operations
\series default
.
 To summarize and to name them, the elementary row operations are
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Swap
\series default
: swap two rows.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Scale
\series default
: multiply each entry in a row by a scalar.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Replace
\series default
: add a multiple of one row to another.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Any system of linear equations can be translated into a matrix and solved
 using these three operations.
 Even systems with no solution reveal themselves as unsolvable under the
 direction of these three operations.
\end_layout

