\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Solving a large system of linear equations, say 5 equations in 5 variables,
 without matrices can be chaotic and confusing.
 Even with matrices solving a system of 5 equations in 5 unknows can be
 chaotic and confusing.
 A systematic approach will allay the chaos.
 The following algorithm describes one approach for solving a system of
 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 equations in 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 unknowns.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Step
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

1: Translate the system into a matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Step
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

2: Let 
\begin_inset Formula $i=k=1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Step
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

3: If 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{i,k}=0$
\end_inset

 
\series bold
swap
\series default
 row 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 with a row below it, say row 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{j,k}\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 If no such row exists, increment 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 by one and try again as long as 
\begin_inset Formula $k\leq n$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 reaches 
\begin_inset Formula $n+1$
\end_inset

, stop.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Step
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

4: 
\series bold
Scale
\series default
 row 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{A_{i,k}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Step
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

5: For each 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $i+1$
\end_inset

 through 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, 
\series bold
replace
\series default
 row 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $-\frac{A_{j,k}}{Ai,k}$
\end_inset

 times row 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 plus row 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Step
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

6: Increment 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 each by one and return to step 3 as long as 
\begin_inset Formula $k\leq n$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Translate the resulting matrix into a system and use back-substitution to
 complete the solution.
 For a computer programmer this description of the algorithm is probably
 good enough.
 The 6 steps outlined form what is essentially pseudo-code for the algorithm.
 For most people, less computerese would be best.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Step
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

1: Select the leftmost column with at least one nonzero entry.
 This is a 
\series bold
pivot column
\series default
.
 The topmost position in this column is a 
\series bold
pivot position
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Step
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

2: If the entry in the pivot position is 0, 
\series bold
swap
\series default
 rows so the entry in the pivot position is nonzero.
 This nonzero entry is a 
\series bold
pivot
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Step
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

3: 
\series bold
Replace
\series default
 rows below the pivot so that all entries below the pivot are 0.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Step
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

4: Repeat steps 1 through 3 on the submatrix consisting of all rows below
 the pivot.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The algorithm concludes as soon as one of these steps cannot be accomplished.
 
\end_layout

